Kitaev arXiv:2405.02434 @ refs/kitaev-2405.02434/approximate_algebras.tex:514-533. sgn(X)=X(X^2)^{-1/2} (defined for ||X^2-x0^2 I||<x0^2), sgn(X)^2=I for all X, ||sgn(X)-X|| <= ||X|| O(||X^2-I||) if ||X^2-I||<1; Prop_P: P in a Banach algebra with ||P^2-P||<=delta<1/4, ~P=theta(2P-I)=(1/2)(I+sgn(2P-I)) satisfies ~P^2=~P EXACTLY, ~P commutes with P, ||~P-P|| <= ||2P-I|| O(delta), proved via X=2P-I with ||X^2-I||<=4delta<1. CAVEAT: constants are literal big-O; the contract's explicit C is DERIVED (node 1.3). Kitaev's home norm is the eps-Banach/cb-norm; the M_n(R) operator-norm arena is the project adaptation (node 1.1). VERBATIM: "\begin{equation}\label{abs_sgn}
|X|=(X^2)^{1/2},\qquad \sgn(X)=X(X^2)^{-1/2}\qquad\quad
\bigl(\|X^2-x_0^2I\|<x_0^2\bigr).
\end{equation}
If $X$ is an approximate solution of the equation $X^2=I$, then a nearby exact solution, commuting with $X$, is given by $\sgn(X)$. Indeed, $\sgn(X)^2=I$ for all $X$, and
\begin{equation}
\|\sgn(X)-X\|\le \|X\|\,O(\|X^2-I\|)\quad\:
\text{if }\, \|X^2-I\|<1.
\end{equation}

\begin{Proposition}\label{prop_P}
Let $P$ be an element of a Banach algebra such that $\|P^2-P\|\le\delta<1/4$, and let
\begin{equation}
\wt{P}=\theta(2P-I),\qquad
\text{where}\quad \theta(X)=\frac{1}{2}\bigl(I+\sgn(X)\bigr).
\end{equation}
Then $\wt{P}^2=\wt{P}$,\, $\wt{P}$ commutes with $P$, and $\|\wt{P}-P\|\le \|2P-I\|\ts O(\delta)$.
\end{Proposition}
\begin{proof} The statement follow from the preceding discussion applied to $X=2P-I$, which satisfies the inequality $\|X^2-I\|\le 4\delta<1$.
\end{proof}"
